PSEUDOCODE
==========

Enable clocks for GPIOA and USART2
Configure PA2 as AF1 (USART2_TX)
Configure USART2:
    BRR  -> set baud rate to 115200 from 16MHz HSI
    Enable TX
    Enable USART2

Loop forever:
    Send string "Hello, World!\r\n" over UART
    Wait for each byte's TXE flag before sending next
    Wait for TC flag after last byte (transmission complete)
    delay_ms(1000)

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

PIN MAP
=======

PA2  ->  USART2_TX (AF1) - connect to ST-Link Virtual COM Port (VCP)
PA3  ->  USART2_RX (AF1) - not used in TX-only program, but noted

On the Nucleo-G071RB, PA2/PA3 are internally wired to the ST-Link USB
bridge. Plug in USB and open a terminal at 115200 8N1 - no external wiring
needed. Here 8N1 refers to 8-data-bits, No parity, 1-stop bit.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

KEY REGISTERS
=============

USART2 (Universal Synchronous/Asynchronous Receiver/Transmitter)
|-------------|------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Register    | Field      | Description                                                                             |
|-------------|------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| USART2->BRR | bits[15:0] | Baud Rate Register. Value = USART_CLK / BAUD. At 16MHz, 115200 baud -> BRR = 139        |
| USART2->CR1 | bit0 UE    | USART Enable. Must be set last, after all config is done                                |
| USART2->CR1 | bit3 TE    | Transmitter Enable. Enables TX path and sends idle frame on the line                    |
| USART2->TDR | bits[8:0]  | Transmit Data Register. Write byte here to send. Triggers transmission                  |
| USART2->ISR | bit 7 TXE  | TX Empty flag. Set when TDR is ready to accept the next byte. Poll before each write    |
| USART2->ISR | bit 6 TC   | Transmission Complete flag. Set when last byte fully shifted out. Poll after final byte |
|-------------|------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|

RCC (Reset and Clock Control)
|--------------|---------------|-------------------------------------------------------|
| Register     | Field         | Description                                           |
|--------------|---------------|-------------------------------------------------------|
| RCC->APBENR1 | bit 17 USART2 | Enables USART2 peripheral clock. USART2 sits on APB1. |
|--------------|---------------|-------------------------------------------------------|

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

KEY CONCEPTS
============

What is USART doing electrically?
At its core, UART/USART is taking a parallel byte sitting in the CPU's memory
and converting it into a serial stream of bits on a single wire, one bit at a
time. The receiver does the reverse.

What is Baud Rate?
Baud rate = number of symbol changes per second on the wire. In UART each symbol
is one bit, so baud rate = bits per second (bps).
* 9600 baud   => 9600 bits per second -> one bit lasts ~104 µs
* 115200 baud => one bit lasts ~8.68 µs

Both sender and receiver must agree on this rate beforehand, there's no clock
wire to negotiate it automatically.

The UART Frame - What's actually on the wire?

Idle  Start  D0   D1   D2   D3   D4   D5   D6   D7   Stop  Idle
HIGH   LOW   b0   b1   b2   b3   b4   b5   b6   b7   HIGH  HIGH
 ‾‾‾‾|_____|____|____|____|____|____|____|____|____|‾‾‾‾‾|‾‾‾‾‾

The start bit is the synchronization mechanism in async UART. The receiver
detects the falling edge (HIGH->LOW), then starts its internal timer and samples
every bit period from that moment.

The Shift Register
The STM32 USART transmitter has two separate hardware registers:
* TRANSMIT DATA REGISTER - TDR
* SHIFT REGISTER

We write to the `TRANSMIT DATA REGISTER` which is automatically copied to a
another register `SHIFT REGISTER` when it is empty. The `SHIFT REGISTER` is
actively shifting bits onto TX pin bit-by-bit.

Without the TDR, we'd have to wait until every single bit has shifted out before
writing the next byte. With TDR, we can write the next byte into TDR while the
previous byte is still shifting out. The moment the shift register finishes, it
immediately pulls the next byte from TDR. This gives us a continuous
back-to-back transmission with no idle gap between bytes.

There is `SHIFT REGISTER` for RDR as well. The shift register collects bits from
RX pin, assembles a full byte, then moves it to RDR and raises an interrupt flag
(RXNE). We then read RDR.

Critical danger: RDR is only 1 byte deep. If we don't read it before the next
byte is fully assembled and tries to move in, we get an Overrun Error (ORE). The
incoming byte is lost. This is why we need interrupts or DMA for reliable
reception.

The CPU and USART machine run in parallel. The CPU drops bytes into TDR and
picks bytes up from RDR. The USART machine handles all the bit-timing,
start/stop bits, oversampling, framing; completely in hardware, without any CPU
cycles. The ISR flags are the USART machine's way of tapping the CPU on the
shoulder and saying "hey, I need attention."

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

COMMON MISTAKES AND DEBUG TIPS
==============================

* BRR rounding error accumulates => 16000000 / 115200 = 138.88. Truncating to
  138 gives a baud rate of 115942 -> 0.64% fast. Rounding to 139 gives
  115107 -> 0.08% slow. UART tolerates up to ~2% error, but rounding is always
  more accurate than truncating. Since we have no hardware divider, the division
  is done once at compile time as a constant, no runtime cost.

* Enabling UE before TE. If we set UE before TE, the transmitter may not
  initialize correctly and the first byte can be corrupted or lost. Always
  configure CR1 fields first, set TE, then set UE last. The code sets them in
  separate |= writes to make the order explicit.

* Not waiting for TC after last byte, TXE goes high as soon as TDR is copied to
  the shift register, the byte is still being clocked out. If we power down,
  sleep, or disable USART right after seeing TXE, the last byte is truncated. TC
  means the shift register is fully empty and the line is idle. Always wait for
  TC at the end of a transmission.

* Garbled output on terminal. Almost always a baud rate mismatch. Double check
  that terminal is set to 115200, 8 data bits, no parity, 1 stop bit (8N1). Also
  verify PA2 maps to the ST-Link VCP on our specific Nucleo revision, some
  boards use different pins.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

EXTRA NOTES
===========

* Why \r\n and not just \n? UART terminals (minicom, PuTTY, Tera Term) typically
  expect \r\n (carriage return + line feed) for a new line. Sending only \n
  causes a staircase effect where each line starts where the previous ended. \r
  moves the cursor to column zero, \n moves it down one row.

* PA2/PA3 and the ST-Link VCP. The Nucleo board has a built-in ST-Link debugger
  chip that bridges USART2 (PA2/PA3) to a USB virtual COM port on our PC. This
  means we get UART output over the same USB cable used for flashing, no
  USB-to-UART adapter needed. This is one of the most convenient features of the
  Nucleo board for development.

* This is the debug backbone from here on. From Program 10 onwards,
  usart2_send_string() and usart2_send_uint_hex() replace any need for a
  debugger watch window for simple value inspection.
